ample 3:\n\nInput: n = 4\nOutput: \"100\"\nExplantion: (-2)2 = 4\n\n \nConstraints:\n\n0 <= n <= 109\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def baseNeg2(self, n: int) -> str:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nclass Solution:\n    def baseNeg2(self, n: int) -> str:\n        if n == 0:\n            return \"0\"\n        \n        result = []\n        while n != 0:\n            n, remainder = divmod(n, -2)\n            if remainder < 0:\n                remainder += 2\n                n += 1\n            result.append(str(remainder))\n        \n        return ''.join(reversed(result))\n```\n\nThis code correctly converts a given integer `n` to its binary representation in base -2. The key steps involve using the `divmod` function to handle the division and remainder, and adjusting the remainder and quotient when the remainder is negative. The result is built in reverse order, so it is reversed before being returned.", "estimated_date": 1553990400000}